00:55:56,959 --> 00:55:58,125
if you ever get out?,"

940
00:55:58,209 --> 00:56:03,167
they'll go, "I'm gonna
come kill you, my friend."

941
00:56:04,626 --> 00:56:09,459
All the information that
came from Abu Zubaydah

942
00:56:09,542 --> 00:56:12,709
we got
before waterboarding.

943
00:56:12,792 --> 00:56:14,250
Most of
these things came

944
00:56:14,334 --> 00:56:17,542
from traditional
interrogation techniques...

945
00:56:17,626 --> 00:56:19,417
by showing people
evidence.

946
00:56:19,500 --> 00:56:21,125
by putting detainees
against each other,

947
00:56:21,209 --> 00:56:22,584
by pocket litter.

948
00:56:22,667 --> 00:56:24,792
So the traditional
interrogation techniques

949
00:56:24,876 --> 00:56:26,542
worked tremendously.

950
00:56:28,751 --> 00:56:30,709
We had the interrogators,

951
00:56:30,792 --> 00:56:32,167
and we had the debriefers.

952
00:56:32,250 --> 00:56:37,167
The interrogators would work
with the detainee.

953
00:56:37,250 --> 00:56:39,626
And once they became
compliant,

954
00:56:39,709 --> 00:56:44,500
they would step back
and the debriefers...

955
00:56:44,584 --> 00:56:48,375
the targeting analysts,
the people who knew the most

956
00:56:48,459 --> 00:56:50,083
about the target
would step in

957
00:56:50,167 --> 00:56:53,959
and would begin
to question them.

958
00:56:54,042 --> 00:56:58,083
Jennifer Matthews was there
sitting in front

959
00:56:58,167 --> 00:57:00,542
of Abu Zubaydah,
asking him questions.

960
00:57:00,626 --> 00:57:02,209
There is
a big difference

